A nine-year study by the University of Calgary revealed that grizzly bears in Banff National Park have the lowest reproductive rate in North America.
Efforts to save female bears have been successful, but the proposal to remove grizzlies from the endangered species list outside Yellowstone raises concerns.
The Bush administration's push for delisting is met with opposition from conservation groups.
Despite the population increase, habitat protection remains crucial for the bears' survival.
The delicate balance of managing the grizzly population highlights the ongoing challenges of wildlife conservation in the face of development pressures.
